WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.260
Good day I'm Norman Wildberger. Today we're going&nbsp;
to talk about division, a very important subject&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.260 --> 00:00:17.400
for primary school education, and we'll have some&nbsp;
interesting things to say about the importance,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:17.400 --> 00:00:24.210
especially of long division, for students. Let's&nbsp;
start with the definition that M divided by N is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:24.210 --> 00:00:34.680
K means that M is K groups of N or K times N. So,&nbsp;
for example, if we want to know what 24 divided by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:34.680 --> 00:00:43.320
4 is, we need to know how many groups of 4 there&nbsp;
are in 24. Well, we can peel off groups of four&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.320 --> 00:00:52.050
one at a time, and now we see that there are one,&nbsp;
two, three, four, five, six groups of four within&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:52.050 --> 00:01:02.040
24, so 24 divided by 4 is 6. This shows that&nbsp;
division is repeated subtraction. We subtract 4,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:06.270
then we subtract another 4, and we subtract&nbsp;
another 4 until we've exhausted the original&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:06.270 --> 00:01:13.200
number. That's also explained by another&nbsp;
notation for division. Instead of M over N,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:13.200 --> 00:01:19.020
sometimes we write M divided by N. This is another&nbsp;
sign for division that resembles subtraction.

00:01:19.020 --> 00:01:24.840
Here are four main laws of division:

00:01:24.840 --> 00:01:28.770
K over M plus N over M equals K plus N over M&nbsp;

00:01:28.770 --> 00:01:35.610
K over M times N over L is K&nbsp;
times N divided by M times L&nbsp;

00:01:35.610 --> 00:01:42.720
K divided by M all over N is&nbsp;
K divided by the product MN&nbsp;

00:01:42.720 --> 00:01:49.500
K divided by M divided by&nbsp;
N is K times N divided by M&nbsp;

00:01:49.500 --> 00:01:55.890
So we're going to look at the proof. We're going&nbsp;
to prove 1 and 4 for you and leave 2 and 3 as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:55.890 --> 00:02:02.190
exercises for you. All right, let's start with&nbsp;
the first law. K divided by M plus N divided by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:02.190 --> 00:02:09.030
M equals K plus N divided by M. Here, the&nbsp;
denominators are the same. Just trying to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:09.030 --> 00:02:13.890
prove something like this, we'll introduce some&nbsp;
notation to make our life easier. We'll decide&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:13.890 --> 00:02:22.020
that K divided by M will be called A, N divided by&nbsp;
M will be called B, and K plus N divided by M will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:22.020 --> 00:02:30.390
be C. So that's A, that's B, that's C, and we want&nbsp;
to prove that A plus B equals C. What do these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:30.390 --> 00:02:38.310
various things mean? This one means that K equals&nbsp;
A times M. This one means that N equals B times M,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:38.310 --> 00:02:46.440
and this one means that K plus N equals C times&nbsp;
M. So we're just unraveling it, connecting it to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:46.440 --> 00:02:56.940
the definition via multiplication. Now, let's look&nbsp;
at K plus N. Here, K plus N is AM plus BM. Here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:58.050 --> 00:03:03.750
the distributive law shows this can be written&nbsp;
as A plus B times M. On the other hand,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:03.750 --> 00:03:11.670
K plus N from here is C times M. So we had&nbsp;
this multiple of M equals this multiple of M,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:11.670 --> 00:03:16.380
so A plus B times M equals C times M. So&nbsp;
that means that A plus B has to equal C.

00:03:16.380 --> 00:03:23.280
For the fourth law, K divided by M divided by&nbsp;
N, which is a little bit strange, is equal to K&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:23.280 --> 00:03:30.930
times N divided by M. We do something similar. We&nbsp;
introduce some notation. We'll let M divided by N,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:30.930 --> 00:03:36.270
which is the denominator here, be A. We&nbsp;
let this entire expression be, say, B,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:36.270 --> 00:03:45.000
and this expression be C. So what we want&nbsp;
to prove is that B equals C. Now we unravel&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:51.780
what these three things mean. This means that M&nbsp;
equals A times N. This means, well, first of all,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:51.780 --> 00:03:57.180
note that M divided by N is really A, so&nbsp;
this is really K divided by K equals B,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:57.180 --> 00:04:06.420
and we unravel it to say K equals B times A, and&nbsp;
this tells us that K times N equals C times M. Now&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:06.420 --> 00:04:13.620
we look at K times N from here. So here's K, and&nbsp;
we're going to multiply it by N, B times N. Then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:13.620 --> 00:04:22.140
we use the associative law to rewrite that as B&nbsp;
times AN. Then we replace the AN with an M to get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.140 --> 00:04:33.880
BM. On the other hand, KN from here is C times M.&nbsp;
So BM equals C times M, and so B and C are equal.

00:04:34.990 --> 00:04:38.950
Now let's say a few words about long&nbsp;
division, a very important skill that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:38.950 --> 00:04:43.570
all students should learn. I realize that&nbsp;
in many curriculums around the world today,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:43.570 --> 00:04:50.410
long division is no longer taught. That is a very&nbsp;
serious mistake. You are essentially undermining&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.410 --> 00:04:56.080
students' ability to learn mathematics if you&nbsp;
don't teach them how to explicitly divide one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:56.080 --> 00:05:01.480
number by another. Here is a simplified way of&nbsp;
doing long division, which is a little bit less&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:01.480 --> 00:05:08.290
efficient than the traditional one but is ideally&nbsp;
suited for students who are not so arithmetically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:08.290 --> 00:05:18.460
gifted. Let's illustrate it by dividing 203 by 7.&nbsp;
First of all, what does it mean? We think of 203&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:18.970 --> 00:05:25.840
as a string of ones, 203 ones in a row. We need&nbsp;
to know how many sevens fit into that string,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:25.840 --> 00:05:31.480
so we want to peel off one seven after another&nbsp;
and count how many sevens we can peel off until&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:31.480 --> 00:05:37.450
we get the whole thing. So what we're going&nbsp;
to do is we're going to subtract multiples&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:37.450 --> 00:05:45.730
of 7 from it and remember how many multiples we&nbsp;
subtracted. First, we look at 203 and ask, well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:45.730 --> 00:05:51.640
how many sevens could safely fit inside there?&nbsp;
We want an underestimate. Well, perhaps twenty&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:51.640 --> 00:06:01.090
sevens fit inside. Twenty times seven is 140, so&nbsp;
we write 140 there. When we subtract 140 from 203,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:01.090 --> 00:06:09.070
we get 63. So after we've peeled off twenty&nbsp;
sevens, there are 63 ones left. How many sevens&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:09.070 --> 00:06:14.380
are there in 63? Well, we remember from our&nbsp;
multiplication tables that 7 times 9 is 63,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:14.380 --> 00:06:20.590
so we peel off nine more sevens, subtract&nbsp;
that to get a remainder of zero. Altogether,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:20.590 --> 00:06:28.930
what we've done is we've subtracted 29&nbsp;
sevens, and so 203 divided by 7 is 29.

00:06:28.930 --> 00:06:39.130
Let's do a slightly more complicated example:&nbsp;
2166 divided by 38. We want to know how many 38&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:39.130 --> 00:06:50.710
fit inside here. We make a guess, perhaps forty,&nbsp;
because four times three is twelve and there'll&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:50.710 --> 00:06:54.490
be a couple of zeros, and the eight will make&nbsp;
it a little bit bigger. If we actually do the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:54.490 --> 00:07:00.910
multiplication, four times 38 is 152, with an&nbsp;
extra zero making 1520. So you may have to do&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:00.910 --> 00:07:10.720
that on the side, that multiplication. So 40&nbsp;
times 38 is 1520. We subtract that from 2166&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:10.720 --> 00:07:20.950
to get 646. Now we ask how many 38s can fit&nbsp;
into 646? Well, let's guess ten. Ten times 38&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:20.950 --> 00:07:30.850
is 380. When we subtract that, we get 266. How&nbsp;
many 38 fit into 266? Well, we might guess six.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:30.850 --> 00:07:40.510
Six times 38 is 228. If you have to do that&nbsp;
multiplication on the side, when we subtract,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:40.510 --> 00:07:47.380
we get 38. How many 38? Well, there's one more 38&nbsp;
that we'll fit in there, and then we'll have zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:47.380 --> 00:07:53.800
Now, as it turns out, we've done this rather&nbsp;
inefficiently. We've subtracted 40 and then we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:53.800 --> 00:07:59.830
subtracted 10. We could have been more efficient&nbsp;
by subtracting 50 all at once. Here we subtracted&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:59.830 --> 00:08:04.300
6 and then we subtracted 1. We could have been&nbsp;
more efficient and subtracted just 7 multiples,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:04.300 --> 00:08:11.530
but it doesn't matter. There's no embarrassment&nbsp;
in taking a few more steps. The main idea is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:11.530 --> 00:08:17.200
that students should know what they're doing:&nbsp;
subtracting a certain multiple of 38 from the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:17.200 --> 00:08:22.210
number and keeping track of how much is left&nbsp;
over, and you keep subtracting 38 until you've&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:22.210 --> 00:08:29.350
got nothing left, then you count up how many&nbsp;
38 you subtracted altogether, in this case 57.

00:08:29.350 --> 00:08:38.170
Let's do another one more example where things&nbsp;
don't quite work out so well. Let's try to divide&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:38.170 --> 00:08:49.570
245 by 17. An initial first guess might be ten.&nbsp;
Ten times 17 is 170. We subtract to get 75. We&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:49.570 --> 00:08:56.850
might guess three 17s fit in there. Three 17s&nbsp;
is 51. We subtract, we get 24 left over. Oh,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:56.850 --> 00:09:03.060
we see we could have actually subtracted one more.&nbsp;
Let's subtract one more now. So there's another 17&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.060 --> 00:09:10.890
and we get seven. But now we're in a situation&nbsp;
where we can't subtract any more 17s from seven;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:10.890 --> 00:09:19.260
seven's too small. So we get a remainder. The&nbsp;
division doesn't quite work out. This divided by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:19.260 --> 00:09:25.080
this is not a natural number, but nevertheless,&nbsp;
we've subtracted fourteen of these 17s,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:25.080 --> 00:09:30.720
so we have seven left over. This remainder means&nbsp;
that although this isn't a natural number answer,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:30.720 --> 00:09:39.180
it is an important stepping stone to our next&nbsp;
topic: fractions, the most challenging subject&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:39.180 --> 00:09:45.390
for primary school students in mathematics. I&nbsp;
hope you'll join me for that. I don't bother.

